He goes on to describe three species growing on the rocks by the sea shore, one of these a native of Creta* and elsewhere speaks of it as communicating a very fast red colour to wool. There can be little doubt that Pliuy, or at least his authorities, intended to indicate by the word sucus some of the ductorial lichena, of which a con- siderable number are found upon maritime rocks in the Mediterranean, and even on our own shores, especially those which yield the red or purple colours, and form the principal constituents of the dye stuff known as arcltl. The most celebrated of these is the roccella taire- lorea, which many modern writers have supposed to be identical with the πάντων φῦκος of Theophrastus, the φῦκος θαλάσσιον of Dioscorides, the phycos tlalassrhn or fucus of Pliny. Dioscorides denies tlrat the paint used by women was made from this plant, and asserta that it was a root bearing the same name, and hence in our dictionaries we find it frequently stated that sucus means the anellum tractoria or alkanet root.
